{
  "id": "geometric-proof-a-plus-b-squared",
  "name": "Geometric Proof of (a + b)²",
  "difficulty": "Algebraic Geometry",
  "description": "This visualization provides a geometric proof for the algebraic identity <b>(a + b)² = a² + 2ab + b²</b>. <br><br>The large square represents the total area of <b>(a + b)²</b>, where the side length is the sum of segments <i>a</i> and <i>b</i>. This area is decomposed into four distinct parts:<br><ul><li>A blue square with area <b>a²</b> (side length <i>a</i>).</li><li>A green square with area <b>b²</b> (side length <i>b</i>).</li><li>Two orange rectangles, each with area <b>ab</b> (sides <i>a</i> and <i>b</i>).</li></ul>By summing these component areas, we visually confirm that (a+b)² = a² + ab + ab + b², which simplifies to the standard quadratic expansion.",
  "tags": [
    "Algebra",
    "Geometry",
    "Visual Proof",
    "Identities"
  ],
